    "finalTextLength": 2489,
    "finalText": "Here’s what you’re missing, based on the evidence:\n\n### 1. Centralized Intake & Tracking\nRight now, too many inbound requests—mail, vendor issues, internal follow-ups—float around with unclear ownership. You need a single queue, visible to everyone, where every item gets an owner, status, and due date. Weekly review, no exceptions. Anything unclaimed gets flagged immediately.\n\n### 2. Document Control & Audit Readiness\nMail, invoices, and tax docs pile up, risking missed payments or audit exposure. Standardize scan/index for everything incoming, with naming conventions that tie docs to project, AP, or finance. Move to a checklist approach: received → reviewed → filed → actioned. No more “I thought someone else handled it.”\n\n### 3. Weekly Execution Rhythm\nSet fixed weekly calendars: check processing and admin review are the same days every week. Separate routine items from overflow/late catch-up. Make the standup short and focused. Review open items, blockers, and near-term deadlines—anything drifting gets a next-step and an owner.\n\n### 4. Follow-Up Ownership Discipline\nOne name next to every open external follow-up. No emailing or calling the same vendor/customer twice (or not at all). Shared outreach log is a must. Escalate overdue responses—don’t let them sit.\n\n### 5. AP / Invoice Control\nInvoices need a strict receipt-to-approval workflow. Timestamped handoffs. Nothing gets paid unless there’s contract/milestone backup attached. Flag exceptions for missing docs, disputes, or unapproved payments before checks get cut.\n\n### 6. Project Milestone Visibility\nMaintain a live milestone schedule—actual, not theoretical. Billing, pay apps, and sub coordination hang off those dates. If a milestone slips, crew planning and cash flow impact get flagged immediately.\n\n### 7. Operational Reporting—Exception-Only\nNo value in weekly status noise. Build a dashboard showing only open mail, outstanding AP, overdue follow-ups, and at-risk milestones. Show what’s off-track, not a bunch of “on track” noise.\n\n---\n\n**Bottom line:**  \nYou need one intake queue, standardized document controls, a weekly admin calendar, single-owner follow-up, and tight AP/billing ties to project milestones. Start simple, then layer in reporting. The biggest risks: falling behind on paperwork, missed follow-ups, cash flow surprises, and milestone slippage.  \nSet these systems up now, or you’ll keep fighting the same fires. Let me know if you want the implementation steps for any of these."
  },
